<TITLE> Three held in Italy over student murder:media </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 LONDON, Nov 6 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - Italian police investigating the murder of British exchange student Meredith Kercher are questioning three suspects, media reports said Tuesday. The 21-year-old's semi-naked body was found at her flat in Perugia, central Italy, on Friday. Her throat had been cut. Media reports said police had been investigating claims she might had been murdered after a sexual encounter and were questioning two men and a woman. Police were holding a news conference later on Tuesday. The Leeds University student from Coulsdon, south London, who was known as "Mez", had been in Italy since August on a 12-month exchange, to study Italian. Her family paid tribute to "one of the most beautiful, intelligent, witty and caring people you could wish to meet". In a statement issued through Scotland Yard, they said the student's murder had "destroyed so many lives". "Words cannot even begin to describe how we feel right now, other than utterly devastated at the tragic loss of our daughter and sister Meredith," they said. "She was pursuing her dream and we can take some comfort in knowing that she has left us at what was a very happy time in her life. "We feel it is no exaggeration to say that Meredith touched the lives of everyone she met with her infectious, upbeat personality, smile and sense of humour." In another tribute, her friends in Perugia held a candlelight vigil on Monday night on the steps of the town's cathedr
